				</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Great civilizations on the American continenent? With no archeological record</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Archaeology is an interesting field.  The discipline requires scientific method but the application is not the same as would be physics.  Saying "with no archaeological record"  is fallacious.  There are a good many artifacts that show a civilisation of hebrew people in the Americas.  They are not widely viewed as significant by contemporary archaeologists and many dispute them.  The arguments available on both side are highly subjective because serious research on oddities that do not fit in "the grand view" are spurned by this one science that is stocked with some of the snootiest narrow minded people you have ever met.
<br />

<br />
There is another stone that was found in Tennesee "the Bat Creek Stone".  The refutations I have read are refutations of another persons hypothesis of origin.  The fact is that it was found by Smithsonian Archaeologists not a farmer. Scientific dating methods puts the time of workmanship period in league with mormon beliefs.   The Hebrew is a little different than found in the Mediteranian but Hebrew would have changed within the isolated hebrews that allegedly traveled here in several hundred years time.
<br />

<br />
<a href="https://listhost.uchicago.edu/pipermail/ane/2004-December/015680.html" target="_blank">https://listhost.uchicago.edu/pipermail/ane/2004-December/015680.html</a>
<br />
<a href="http://www.econ.ohio-state.edu/jhm/arch/decalog.html" target="_blank">http://www.econ.ohio-state.edu/jhm/arch/decalog.html</a>
<br />

<br />
The unfortunate thing is that the subjective nature of the subject allows for very broad projection.  The jury is out for me on the authenticity of these artifacts and others found in the Americas.  But clearly saying that there is no record is not plainly true.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Prophets no one else has heard of?</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Today you are Fallon the Fallacious <img src="images/smiles/smile.gif" alt="smile" border="0" />  There is plenty that "no one" else has heard of  in ancient history.  Bad argument.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Whatever else you can say of the Bible, there is supporting archeological and historical material.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
